05495nam a2200829Ia 9780271096629DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710966297 a10.1515/97802710966292doi  a(DE-B1597)667063  a(OCoLC)1395906742  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a817/.4092221 aThompson, Todd Nathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Laughable Empire :bThe US Imagines the Pacific World, 1840–1890 /cTodd Nathan Thompson. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHumor in America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Backwoodsman Abroad: The Pacific Imperialism of Nineteenth-Century American Humor -- t2. Comic Currents: Polynesians in Periodicals -- t3. “Cheering for Ye, Cannibal”: The Politics of Boiled Missionaries -- t4. Collecting the Pacific: A Cabinet of Comic Curios -- t5. “Didn’t Our People Laugh?” Humor as Resistance -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Detailed Information on Reprinted Jokes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the nineteenth-century United States, jokes, comic anecdotes, and bons mots about the Pacific Islands and Pacific Islanders tried to make the faraway and unfamiliar either understandable or completely incomprehensible (i.e., “other”) to American readers. A Laughable Empire examines this substantial archival corpus, attempting to make sense of nineteenth-century American humor about Hawai‘i and the rest of the Pacific world.Todd Nathan Thompson collects and interprets these comic, sometimes racist depictions of Pacific culture in nineteenth-century American print culture. Drawing on an archive of almanac and periodical humor, sea yarns, jest books, and literary comedy, Thompson demonstrates how jokes and humor functioned sometimes in the service of and sometimes in resistance to US imperial ambitions. Thompson also includes Indigenous voices and jokes lampooning Americans and their customs to show how humor served as an important cultural contact zone between the United States and the Pacific world. He considers how nineteenth-century Americans and Pacific Islanders alike used humor to employ stereotypes or to question them, to “other” the unknown or to interrogate, laughingly, the process by which “othering” occurs and is disseminated.Incisive and detailed, A Laughable Empire documents American humor about Pacific geography, food, dress, speech, and customs. Thompson sheds new light not only on nineteenth-century America’s imperial ambitions but also on its deep anxieties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAmerican wit and humory19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aPacific Islanders in literature. 0aPacific IslandersxHumorxHistoryy19th century. 0aSatire, Americany19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology) in literature. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aBarnum.  aHerman Melville.  aHumor.  aMark Twain.  aPacific.  acannibal-and-boiled-missionary.  acannibalism.  acolonialism.  acomic almanacs.  ajokes.  aperiodicals.  aracism.  areprinting.  asatire.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter